    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im seeing some weirdness in our ec2 instances. getting \"Connection reset by peer\" errors in the logs every few hours but it's totally intermittent. here is a snippet of the cloudwatch log:\n\n2023-10-24T14:22:01Z i-0a1234567890abcdef error: connection reset by peer (errno 104)\n2023-10-24T14:25:12Z i-0a1234567890abcdef error: connection reset by peer (errno 104)\n\nany idea if this could be a security group or NACL thing? or should i look at the app layer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Connection reset by peer errors, especially intermittent ones, are a classic sign that something is abruptly closing the connection, which can be caused by a few things. You should definitely check your security groups and Network ACLs first, as those are the first line of defense, or if you're dealing with a specific application protocol, then look at the application layer.\n\nLook at the security group rules for the EC2 instance and the associated load balancer or other communicating services. Sometimes, a misconfigured rule, or a stateful inspection issue in the network layer, can cause this. If the network layer is clean, then you'll need to dig into the application logs.",
      "source": "target",
